Motivation

Question: You’ve learned linear regression predicts continuous outcomes (salary, house prices). What if we want to predict a binary outcome like:

  • Will a customer default on their loan? (Yes/No)
  • Is this email spam? (Yes/No)
  • Does a patient have a disease? (Yes/No)

Why not just use linear regression?

Think about it: What problems might arise if we try to fit a line to predict 0s and 1s?

Today’s Goal:

We’ll discover why classification requires different tools, and more importantly, why evaluating classification models is fundamentally different from evaluating regression models.

Regression vs Classification

  • Regression: predict a continuous / quantitative outcome (e.g., salary, house price).
    • Evaluation metrics we used previously: Mean Squared Error (MSE), Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE), R-squared
  • Classification: predict a categorical outcome (e.g., default: Yes / No)

Why the distinction matters: evaluation metrics and modeling choices differ.

Why not use linear regression?

If we naively regress the binary outcome on predictors, problems arise:

  • Predictions can fall outside [0,1]
  • Residuals and error distribution assumptions fail

Instead, classification approaches or probability-based methods are used; for now we focus on classification evaluation.

Variables we will use:

  • default: factor with levels No, Yes (response)
  • balance: monthly credit card balance (predictor)
  • income: annual income (predictor)
  • student: Yes/No (qualitative predictor)

Balance vs Income scatter plot by default

  • What patterns do you notice?

Class distribution

Default %>% 
  count(default) %>% 
  mutate(pct = n / sum(n))
##   default    n    pct
## 1      No 9667 0.9667
## 2     Yes  333 0.0333

Note: this dataset is imbalanced – only a small fraction of observations default.

  • Can be a common isue with classification data

Boxplot: balance by default

Observation: defaulting customers tend to have higher balances on average.

Classification goal

Given features (balance, income, student), assign each customer to Yes or No for default.

Two broad pieces:

  1. A rule (classifier) that maps features to a predicted class.
    • Given the class imbalance in our dataset, what would be a decent prediction?
  2. An evaluation scheme to quantify how good the rule is.

Baseline (naive) classifier

  • A simple baseline: always predict No (i.e., assume nobody defaults).
  • This is a useful sanity-check for any classifier on imbalanced data.

We’ll compute metrics for this baseline.

Introduction to Confusion Matrix

For binary classification (positive = Yes default) there are four different possibilities:

Predicted Yes Predicted No
Actual Yes True Positive (TP) False Negative (FN)
Actual No False Positive (FP) True Negative (TN)
  • Confusion matrix summarizes correct and incorrect predictions and are the basis for our performance metrics.

Compute confusion matrix with dplyr

# Actual truth
truth <- Default$default
# Our naive prediction of no default for all
Default <- Default %>% mutate(pred_baseline = factor("No", levels = levels(default)))
# Use table for confusion matrix
table(Actual = Default$default, Predicted = Default$pred_baseline)
##       Predicted
## Actual   No  Yes
##    No  9667    0
##    Yes  333    0

Question: What are the TP, FP, TN, FN values in this confusion matrix?

  • True Positive (TP): Correctly predicting a customer will default (helps us avoid bad loans).
  • False Positive (FP): Predicting default when the customer would have paid (lost business opportunity).
  • True Negative (TN): Correctly predicting no default (safe loans granted).
  • False Negative (FN): Predicting no default when the customer actually defaults (a missed risky case).

For loan business, need to figure out how aggressive we want to be

Accuracy and Error Rate

Definition: Accuracy measures the overall proportion of correct predictions, while Error Rate measures the proportion of incorrect predictions.

Formulas:
- Accuracy = (TP + TN) / (TP + TN + FP + FN)
- Error Rate = (FP + FN) / (TP + TN + FP + FN)

Default %>%
  summarise(
    accuracy = mean(pred_baseline == default),
    error_rate = 1 - mean(pred_baseline == default)
  )
##   accuracy error_rate
## 1   0.9667     0.0333

Precision

Definition: Precision (positive predictive value) is the fraction of predicted Yes cases that are actually Yes. High precision means few false positives.

Formula: Precision = TP / (TP + FP)

Default %>%
  summarise(
    precision = sum(pred_baseline == "Yes" & default == "Yes") /
                sum(pred_baseline == "Yes")
  )
##   precision
## 1       NaN

Recall

Definition: Recall (sensitivity) is the fraction of actual Yes cases that are correctly predicted. High recall means few false negatives.

Formula: Recall = TP / (TP + FN)

Default %>%
  summarise(
    recall = sum(pred_baseline == "Yes" & default == "Yes") /
             sum(default == "Yes")
  )
##   recall
## 1      0

Specificity

Definition: Specificity is the fraction of actual No cases that are correctly predicted as No. High specificity means few false positives.

Formula: Specificity = TN / (TN + FP)

Default %>%
  summarise(
    specificity = sum(pred_baseline == "No" & default == "No") /
                  sum(default == "No")
  )
##   specificity
## 1           1

Summary of Performance Metrics

Default %>% summarise(
  Accuracy = mean(pred_baseline == default),
  Error_Rate = 1 - mean(pred_baseline == default),
  Precision = sum(pred_baseline == "Yes" & default == "Yes") / sum(pred_baseline == "Yes"),
  Recall = sum(pred_baseline == "Yes" & default == "Yes") / sum(default == "Yes"),
  Specificity = sum(pred_baseline == "No" & default == "No") / sum(default == "No")
)
##   Accuracy Error_Rate Precision Recall Specificity
## 1   0.9667     0.0333       NaN      0           1
  • Accuracy looks good but NaN Precision and 0 Recall should raise red flags
  • What is the main risk here?

Simple rule-based classifier

  • Our earlier analysis showed high balance loans tend to default.
  • Predict Yes if balance > 2000, else No. Compare its metrics to the naive classifier.

Metrics comparison

Metric Baseline (Always ‘No’) Rule (Balance > 2000)
Accuracy 0.967 0.972
Precision NaN 0.764
Recall 0.000 0.243
Specificity 1.000 0.997
  • Accuracy increased slightly - both models have high accuracy (96.7% → 97.2%), but this masks important differences
  • Precision & Recall: Baseline can’t identify any defaulters (NaN precision, 0% recall)
  • Rule-based classifier: Now catches some defaulters! Much better recall.
  • Trade-off: Slightly lower specificity means we’re rejecting some good customers

Bottom line: The simple rule is far more useful than the naive baseline, even though accuracy alone doesn’t show this clearly.

Imbalanced classes: why accuracy can mislead

Because only a small percent default, a classifier that predicts No for everyone attains high accuracy but is useless for catching defaulters.

Hence alternative metrics (precision, recall, specificity) are crucial.

F1 Score and Balanced Accuracy

  • Balanced accuracy = Average of how well we predict each class separately
    • Regular accuracy can be high just by getting the majority class right
    • Balanced accuracy = (Recall + Specificity) / 2
    • Treats both classes (Yes and No) as equally important
  • F1 score = harmonic mean of Precision and Recall; balances false positives and false negatives.
    • 2 * Precision * Recall / (Precision + Recall)
Metric Baseline (Always ‘No’) Rule (Balance > 2000)
Accuracy 0.967 0.972
Balanced Accuracy 0.500 0.620
F1 Score 0.000 0.369

Key Insights:

  • Balanced accuracy reveals the naive classifier performs at chance (50%) for detecting defaulters
  • F1 score of 0 (or NaN) for baseline is a major red flag - it catches no positives
  • Rule-based classifier shows meaningful improvement on both metrics

Wrap-up / Key takeaways

  • Classification predicts categorical outcomes – evaluation must focus on class-specific performance.
  • Confusion matrices make trade-offs explicit (TP, FP, TN, FN).
  • Accuracy can be misleading on imbalanced datasets; examine precision, recall, specificity, and F1.
  • Simple rule-based classifiers can illustrate trade-offs before moving to probabilistic models (e.g., logistic regression) or more complex learners.
